:: Enigma / wartime cryptography {"position":"1175,1075","size":"100,100"}
<h2 id="enigma-/-wartime-cryptography">Enigma / wartime cryptography</h2>

<div class = "obscure-in">
<p><img  src = "https://www.mub.eps.manchester.ac.uk/science-engineering/wp-content/uploads/sites/59/2018/11/Enigma-3.jpg"
alt = "enigma machine"
height = auto
width = auto /></p>

<p>The Enigma machine was used by Nazi Germany during World War II to encrypt military and diplomatic communications. Unlike simpler substitution ciphers, Enigma relied on a system of rotating rotors, electrical circuits, and daily key settings that changed the way each letter was encoded. This made the machine far more complex than earlier hand-made codes, because the same letter could be encrypted differently each time it was typed. To German forces, Enigma appeared to provide a fast and highly secure method of protecting sensitive wartime messages.</p>
<p>
Its importance went far beyond technology. Enigma was used to send information about troop movements, naval operations, battlefield plans, and supply coordination. Because so much of Germany’s military communication depended on it, breaking Enigma became one of the most important intelligence goals of the war. Polish mathematicians made some of the earliest major breakthroughs before the war, and later British codebreakers at Bletchley Park, including Alan Turing and many others, expanded that work to help read German encrypted traffic.</p>
<p>
The successful effort to break Enigma had a major impact on the war. Intelligence gathered from decrypted messages gave the Allies insight into German strategy and helped them respond more effectively in the Atlantic and in Europe. Historians often point to Enigma as proof that cryptography and codebreaking were not just background technical skills, but forces that could shape military decisions and alter the course of history. The story of Enigma also marks an important moment in the development of modern computing, because the machines and methods created to attack it helped lay groundwork for later advances in computer science and cybersecurity.</p>

</div>

<p>
Deeper Dive: [[Caesar cipher]]
Deeper Dive: [[How encryption evolved over time]]
</p>


[[History of Encryption]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 

<p>Source: <a href="https://www.nsa.gov/portals/75/documents/about/cryptologic-heritage/historical-figures-publications/publications/wwii/german_cipher.pdf?" target="_blank">
  German Cipher Machines of WWII
</a></p>


:: HTTP/ secure websites {"position":"2375,600","size":"100,100"}
<h2>HTTP/ secure websites</h2>

<div class = "bounce-in-top">
<p><img  src = "https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20240111152750/HTTPS-gif.gif
"
alt = "https"
height = auto
width = auto /></p>

<p>When a website uses HTTPS, it means the connection between your browser and the site is protected with encryption. This helps keep information private as it moves across the internet, including things like usernames, passwords, payment details, and personal data. It is one of the main reasons people can safely log in, shop, and submit information online.</p>

<p>
Secure websites are important because data often passes through many systems before reaching its destination. Without encryption, that information could be read or stolen more easily while in transit. HTTPS helps reduce that risk by making the connection between the user and the website much harder for outsiders to monitor or tamper with.
</p>
</div>

<p>
Deep Dive: [[Passwords]]
Deep Dive: [[Online banking]]
Deep Dive: [[Text messaging]]
</p>


[[Encryption in Everyday Life]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 


:: History of Encryption {"position":"1175,950","size":"100,100"}
<h1 id="history-of-encryption">History of Encryption</h1>


<div class="scale-in-center">

<p><img  src = "https://informationsecuritybuzz.com/wp-content/uploads/Untitled62.png
"
alt = "history of encryption"
height = auto
width = auto />
</p>

<p>Encryption has existed in many forms throughout human history, adapting to the needs and technologies of each era. In the ancient world, people used basic methods such as letter substitutions, symbol replacements, and rearranged writing to hide military plans, political messages, and other sensitive information from enemies. Over time, these techniques became more organized and sophisticated, especially during periods of war and diplomacy, when protecting communication could mean the difference between success and failure. Although early systems were often simple by modern standards, they introduced the central idea behind encryption: transforming readable information into a form that outsiders could not easily understand.

In the modern world, encryption has become far more advanced and far more essential. Instead of relying mainly on secret alphabets or manual ciphers, today’s systems use complex mathematical algorithms and digital keys to secure data across computers, phones, websites, and networks. Encryption now protects online banking, financial transactions, passwords, private messages, business records, government systems, and personal files stored in the cloud. Even though the tools have changed dramatically, the underlying purpose remains the same as it was centuries ago: to preserve confidentiality, protect valuable information, and keep it safe from unauthorized access.</p>
</div>

<div class="slide-in-left">
<p>
Deeper Dive: [[Caesar cipher]]
Deeper Dive: [[Enigma / wartime cryptography]]
Deeper Dive: [[How encryption evolved over time]]
</p>



