:: How encryption evolved over time {"position":"1300,1075","size":"100,100"}
<h2>How encryption evolved over time</h2>

Secret writing has existed for thousands of years. Early forms appeared in the Old Testament, where the word Sheshach was used in place of Babel (Babylon) through a substitution method called athbash, which reversed the Hebrew alphabet. Ancient Babylonians, Assyrians, Egyptians, and Greeks also used early forms of coded communication, including both substitution and transposition methods.

Modern cryptography began to take shape during the Italian Renaissance, when diplomacy increased the need for private communication. In 1466, Leone Battista Alberti developed the polyalphabetic principle, which became the foundation for many later ciphers. In 1508, Johannes Trithemius introduced the square table in Polygraphia, helping advance more systematic encryption methods.

Cryptography and codebreaking became especially important during the two World Wars. In World War I, the interception and decryption of the Zimmermann Note helped push the United States into the war. In World War II, breaking enemy codes, along with the use of the Navajo language in coded military communication, played a major role in Allied success.



<p>
Deeper Dive: [[Caesar cipher]]
Deeper Dive: [[Enigma / wartime cryptography]]
</p>

[[History of Encryption]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 

<p>Source: <a href="https://kids.britannica.com/students/article/ciphers-and-codes/273673#:~:text=Crytograms%20have%20been%20found%20in%20the%20Old%20Testament" target="_blank">
  History of Secret Writing
</a></p>


:: Human error {"position":"1800,1000","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Human error</h2>

<div class = "obscure-in">
<p><img  src = "https://www.f-secure.com/i/500x345/e83c76faa8/what-is-social-engineering.svg
"
alt = "burglar"
height = auto
width = auto /></p>
<p>
Even when encryption itself is strong, security can still break down because of human error. People may accidentally send confidential information to the wrong person, reuse weak or stolen passwords, ignore security warnings, or fail to protect private keys and other sensitive credentials. Attackers also take advantage of human behavior through social engineering, which includes tactics like phishing, fake login pages, and deceptive messages designed to trick users into revealing information or taking unsafe actions. In many cases, the weakness is not the encryption system itself, but the decisions people make while using it. This is why real security depends on both reliable technology and informed, careful human behavior.
</p>
</div>

<p>
Dive Deeper: [[Weak passwords]]
Dive Deeper: [[Privacy vs surveillance]]
Dive Deeper: [[Can encryption be misused?]]
</p>

