:: Online banking {"position":"2125,600","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Online bankning</h2>

<div class = "bounce-in-top">
<p><img  src = "https://lkmoneymgmt.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/iStock-682395884.tashka2000.online.banking-5c7474ef46e0fb00018bd6c5.jpg
"
alt = "online banking"
height = 600px
width = 900px /></p>

<p>Online banking depends heavily on encryption to protect financial information. When people check balances, transfer money, or pay bills online, encryption helps keep account details and transactions private. This is essential because financial data is highly sensitive and valuable to criminals.</p>

<p>Banks also combine encryption with other security measures, such as account authentication and fraud detection. Encryption alone does not solve every security problem, but it plays a major role in making digital banking possible. Without it, online banking would be much riskier and far less trustworthy for everyday users.</p>
</div>

<p>
Deep Dive: [[Passwords]]
Deep Dive: [[HTTP/ secure websites]]
Deep Dive: [[Text messaging]]
</p>


[[Encryption in Everyday Life]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 


:: Passwords {"position":"2250,600","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Passwords</h2>

<p>Passwords are often the first barrier protecting personal accounts and devices. While a password itself is not the same thing as encryption, it is closely connected because passwords are often used to control access to encrypted information. A strong password makes it harder for attackers to break into an account or unlock protected data.</p>
<p>
Weak passwords create a major problem because they can undermine security even when strong encryption is being used. If someone chooses a short, common, or reused password, an attacker may be able to guess it and gain access anyway. This shows that security depends not just on the technology, but also on the choices people make.</p>


<p>
Deep Dive: [[HTTP/ secure websites]]
Deep Dive: [[Online banking]]
Deep Dive: [[Text messaging]]
</p>


[[Encryption in Everyday Life]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 


:: Plaintext vs ciphertext {"position":"300,325","size":"100,100"}
<h2 id="plaintext-vs-ciphertext">Plaintext vs Ciphertext</h2>
[[Main Lobby]] 

<p>Data before encryption is referred to as plaintext, whereas the data after encryption is referred to as ciphertext. These two phrases are frequently used when discussing encryption and encrypted data.</p>

<table class="obscure-in">
  <tr>
    <th>Category</th>
    <th>Description</th>
    <th>Cipher Text</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Definition</td>
    <td>Original readable data in natural form</td>
    <td>Encrytped text, not easily readable</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Accessibility</td>
    <td>It can be understood without decryption</td>
    <td>Requires decryption to understand</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Representation</td>
    <td>Represents the actual content of the message</td>
    <td>Represents an encrypted version of the message</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Security</td>
    <td>Prone to unauthorized access</td>
    <td>Offeres greater security against breaches</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Conversion</td>
    <td>Input to encryptions, output to decryption</td>
    <td>Output of encryption, input to decryption</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Purpose</td>
    <td>Easily read and understood by humans</td>
    <td>Secure transmission and storage of data</td>
  </tr>
</table>


<p>Deeper Dive: [[Why people encrypt information]]</p>

<p>
[[What Is Encryption?]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 
</p>


