  Encryption Consulting
</a></p>



:: Privacy vs surveillance {"position":"1925,1000","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Privacy vs surveillance</h2>

<div class = "obscure-in">
<p><img  src = "https://thumbs.dreamstime.com/b/big-brother-watching-you-spying-eyes-surveillance-privacy-concept-vector-illustration-vintage-personal-data-violation-119487817.jpg
"
alt = "big brother"
height = auto
width = auto /></p>

<p>Encryption helps protect privacy by keeping messages and data safe from unwanted access. For individuals, encryption helps preserve personal freedom, confidentiality, and control over private communication. It can protect people from identity theft, cybercrime, and unwanted surveillance by outsiders.</p>

<p>At the same time, strong encryption has become a point of tension for governments and law enforcement agencies. Officials sometimes argue that when encrypted devices or messages cannot be accessed, criminal investigations and national security efforts can become more difficult.This creates an ongoing debate between two important values: personal privacy and public security.</p>
</div>

<p>
Dive Deeper: [[Weak passwords]]
Dive Deeper: [[Human error]]
Dive Deeper: [[Can encryption be misused?]]
</p>


[[Limits, Risks, and Ethics]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 

