:: Text messaging {"position":"2250,725","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Text messaging</h2>

<p>Encryption is also used in modern text and messaging services to help keep conversations private. In some apps, messages are protected so that only the sender and the intended recipient can read them. This helps prevent others from easily intercepting or viewing private conversations.</p>

<p>This is especially important because people often use messaging apps to share personal thoughts, photos, addresses, and other sensitive information. Encrypted messaging gives users more privacy and control over who can access their communication. As digital communication becomes more common, message encryption has become a major part of daily online safety.</p>

<p>
Deep Dive: [[Passwords]]
Deep Dive: [[HTTP/ secure websites]]
Deep Dive: [[Online banking]]
</p>


[[Encryption in Everyday Life]] 
[[Main Lobby]] 


:: Weak passwords {"position":"1675,1000","size":"100,100"}
<h2>Weak passwords</h2>

<div class = "obscure-in">
<p><img  src = "https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSpiF7WAxpXGLt3lSJsZexa_j8oJq7NnEfF3Q&s
"
alt = "weak password"
height = auto
width = auto /></p>


<p>
Encryption can protect data, but weak passwords can still leave an account or file easy to break into. If a password is too short, common, or reused, attackers may guess it or crack it through automated attacks. In other words, strong encryption is much less effective when the password protecting it is weak. Humans are not good at remembering long, random secrets, so they often create passwords that are easy to guess. To reduce the security risk this creates, online services use password rules designed to make those passwords stronger.
</p>
</div>

<p>
